scans.furtherComments: Post XRT to thorax    There has been a positive response to therapy in the thorax, with reduction in  size of previous aortopulmonary and left hilar lymph nodes and only mild  residual FDG uptake in the left hilar nodes suggests a very good partial  metabolic response to therapy.    No recurrent disease or active lymphadenopathy is seen in the right side of the  neck in the setting of previous neck dissection.    There is new uptake in the L1 vertebral body in keeping with a skeletal  metastasis and there is corresponding lucency on CT.    Appearances raise the possibility of an early soft tissue metastasis in the left  gluteus maximus muscle that is difficult to appreciate on CT.    Increased activity in the oesophagus and left lung likely relates to post  radiation inflammation and reduced activity in the upper thoracic and cervical  spine is also in keeping with previous radiotherapy.

There has been progressive soft tissue disease, with an enlarging soft tissue  nodule in the left gluteus maximus muscle and a new subcutaneous nodule in the  left inguinal region adjacent to the anterior iliac crest. A further new soft  tissue lesion is seen in the right deltoid region.  No local recurrence or nodal disease is seen in the right side of the neck.  No pulmonary or hepatic metastasis has been demonstrated.

The left gluteal and left iliac crest soft tissue metastases have  increased in size. The appearances elsewhere are stable. No new lesion, in  particular no brain metastasis. Professor Millward has been informed.

There has been considerable reduction size of the metastases evident  within the left gluteal musculature and also within the subcutaneous region just  above the level of the left inguinal ligament.    Right hilar nodal tissue has shown at least mild reduction in bulk. Stable L1  lesion.
Stable residual right hilar lymph node and left gluteal metastasis.  No new lesion is seen.

Stable disease. There is no evidence of recurrent left hilar or  mediastinal lymphadenopathy. Treated osseous metastases are stable and no new  metastasis is identified.

INTERPRETATION:	  1.	Disease progression since the 23/11/17 external PET, with evidence of widespread metastatic disease.   2.	Multiple liver and skeletal metastases, predominantly in axial skeleton but also involving distal left femur.    3.	Subcutaneous metastases in the back on either side.   4. This shows no discernible enhancement in the post-gadolinium scans nor is there any surrounding vasogenic oedema. It was not present on the previous MRI from 22 November 2017 and potentially represents an inadvertently treated metastasis if the patient has received chemotherapy.    here is marrow replacement in keeping with metastatic disease involving T5 and T6 vertebra with a compression fracture of T6 and 50 to 60% loss of height. There is no significant intraspinal or paravertebral enhancing soft tissue mass.    No significant extrinsic compression upon the thoracic cord or intrinsic cord lesion is identified.

Comment: There is a somewhat mixed response but there is overall disease progression. There are new and progressive metastases at the right periparotid region. The majority of the patient's osseous metastases demonstrate advance. There is slightly variable response at peripheral soft tissue metastases. Activity can be seen at a nodule within the right lung lower lobe but the remaining pulmonary nodules are too small to assess at PET. Concurrent CT shows progressive pulmonary and liver metastases. It is possible that the advance in disease occurred in the interval before treatment commenced however.

Comment: The 3 mm T1 hyperintense nodule at the depth of the right superior frontal sulcus has not changed since the MR on 6 April 2018.    No other new parenchymal or leptomeningeal enhancement identified.

scans.furtherComments: Baseline with mets    1.	The large right axillary melanoma mass is intensely FDG-avid, as would be expected.   2.	Multiple small bilateral pulmonary nodules. These nodules are of long standing but have slowly progressed on CT since 2016. Several of the small nodules are mild to moderately FDG-avid, with progression in metabolic activity since the previous PET-CT in September 2018. Metastatic papillary thyroid cancer is favoured over melanoma in view of the very slow progression and an elevated thyroglobulin (post-thyroidectomy). Repeat thyroglobulin is suggested.  3.	Mild activity in small bilateral upper cervical nodes is stable and more likely benign.  4.	No evidence of metastatic melanoma and thyroid cancer elsewhere.

Heterogeneously enhancing right axillary mass sandwiched between the right pectoralis major and minor musculature.  It is intimately related to the right subclavian vessels and the proximal portion of the right axillary vessels, draped along their anterior margins. Stable multiple bilateral pulmonary nodules as before.  No visible destructive lesion in the thorax or neck.  No mediastinal, hilar, supraclavicular or cervical lymphadenopathy identified.

1.	The current scan demonstrates several interval changes since the prior study which are difficult to unify on metabolic grounds.  2.	Extensive new avid right axillary nodes are highly suspicious of metastatic progression, with disease extending to the axillary apex / subpectoral region and right lateral chest wall.  Elliptical hypodensity in the surgical bed is likely attributable to a residual post-surgical collection.  3.	Interval increase in volume of avid bilateral pulmonary nodules with generalised parenchymal nodularity; these are indeterminate and difficult to differentiate between malignant (melanoma vs. thyroid) and benign (immune-related) aetiologies. Mild heterogeneous bilateral pleural uptake (R>L) is favoured to be inflammatory in nature.  4.	Symmetrical mediastinal/hilar nodes and upper abdominal nodal cluster raises the possibility of a granulomatous process, with nodal metastases a possible differential. Diffuse splenic uptake is likely reactive.  5.	Diffuse marrow uptake is likely reactive; the foci of relative prominence are less specific, and the possibility of osseous metastasis cannot be excluded.  6.	CT chest suggested to further characterise the lung changes, and early FDG-PET/CT follow up could potentially help to clarify current findings

There has been significant reduction in the extent of metabolic activity at the right axilla in response to targeted radiotherapy.   2.	Elsewhere there has been very significant progression of disease with multiple new large bilateral pulmonary metastases, hepatic metastasis, progressive thoracic adenopathy and very extensive skeletal metastatic disease involving the axial and appendicular skeleton.    3.	Diffuse colonic activity is consistent with inflammation
